        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hosea 4:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). To make the ears heavy (hikhbı̄d), away from hearing, i.e., so that they do not hear (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 6:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). To make the heart diamond (shâmı̄r), i.e., as hard as diamond. A stony heart is a heart not susceptible to impressions (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 11:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The relative אשׁר before shâlach refers to the two nouns named before, viz., tōrâh and debhârı̄m, though we need not on that account take tōrâh in the general sense of instruction. God also sent the law to the people through the prophets, i.e., caused them to preach it and impress it upon their hearts. The consequence of this obduracy of the people was, that \"there arose great wrath from Jehovah\" (cf. ",
        "children": []
